WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:08.460
I want you to imagine, just for a second, that you are looking at a finalized, beautifully formatted PDF document.

00:08.800 --> 00:12.320
Right, like a really polished corporate report or something.

00:12.360 --> 00:18.520
Exactly. It's perfect. The margins are aligned. The text is crisp. The arguments flow logically.

00:18.520 --> 00:27.760
And if I were to ask you, you know, what is this document? You would probably just point to the words on the page.

00:27.760 --> 00:30.340
Yeah, you would describe its current state.

00:30.480 --> 00:33.400
You'd say, oh, it's a 10-page report on market trends.

00:33.540 --> 00:33.740
Yeah.

00:34.060 --> 00:39.340
And in our normal day-to-day lives, that answer is perfectly acceptable.

00:39.740 --> 00:46.640
I mean, we are totally obsessed with the snapshot. We define things by what they are right now in this exact moment.

00:46.820 --> 00:49.780
We do. We prioritize the result over the process.

00:49.780 --> 00:57.840
But what if I told you that looking at that PDF tells you, well, almost nothing about the true reality of that document?

00:58.200 --> 01:08.900
What if the actual identity of that document isn't the final text at all, but the hidden, agonizing history of every single typo that was deleted?

01:09.040 --> 01:12.780
Or every entire paragraph that was highlighted and scrapped.

01:12.840 --> 01:17.820
Yes, and every alternative phrasing that the author considered but ultimately rejected.

01:17.820 --> 01:22.040
It completely upends our fundamental definition of reality.

01:22.400 --> 01:31.620
Because when you shift your focus from the final polished output to the messy, irreversible sequence of things that were thrown away.

01:31.760 --> 01:32.020
Right.

01:32.280 --> 01:38.960
You stop looking at a static object and you start looking at a living timeline of sacrifices.

01:38.960 --> 01:50.880
And that profound shift in perspective is exactly why I am so incredibly thrilled to welcome you, yes, you listening to us right now, to this deep dive.

01:51.320 --> 01:53.800
I know we have listeners from all walks of life.

01:53.920 --> 01:57.120
I mean, maybe you are prepping for a high-stakes strategy meeting.

01:57.260 --> 02:03.020
Or maybe you're a developer trying to catch up on the absolute bleeding edge of computational theory.

02:03.020 --> 02:10.180
Or maybe you are just one of those insanely curious people who loves pulling apart the fabric of how the universe works.

02:10.300 --> 02:10.900
Exactly.

02:11.300 --> 02:14.420
Whatever brought you here, you have arrived at the perfect time.

02:14.720 --> 02:18.740
Because today, we are tearing down our obsession with the snapshot.

02:19.520 --> 02:28.300
We are going to explore a radical new framework for understanding how choices, computers, and honestly, even the human mind actually function.

02:28.300 --> 02:38.820
And we're going to give you those vital aha moments, breaking down an incredibly complex system without, you know, leaving you feeling overwhelmed by the jargon.

02:39.360 --> 02:42.400
We have an amazing stack of source material to guide us today.

02:42.580 --> 02:43.220
We really do.

02:43.400 --> 02:52.480
We are diving into a series of incredibly dense, mathematically rigorous, and yet deeply philosophical papers by an author known as Flixian.

02:53.000 --> 02:53.560
Flixian.

02:53.900 --> 02:56.160
It's such a fascinating body of work.

02:56.320 --> 02:56.740
It is.

02:56.740 --> 03:01.680
These texts introduce a comprehensive theoretical framework called SpherePop.

03:02.220 --> 03:16.520
We'll be pulling insights from specific papers in this collection, including titles like History as Identity, The Joy of SpherePop, and the highly technical architectural blueprint known as SpherePop Specifications.

03:16.520 --> 03:33.160
The mission of this deep dive is to explore what happens when we stop defining our world, our technology, and ourselves by our current state, and start defining everything by the unchangeable, irreversible history of choices that got us here.

03:33.920 --> 03:34.940
It's a wild ride.

03:35.200 --> 03:36.580
Okay, let's unpack this.

03:36.580 --> 03:46.800
So, to truly appreciate the earthquake that Flixian is causing with SpherePop, we first have to understand the foundational concrete of the building they are trying to demolish.

03:47.120 --> 03:48.980
We have to understand what they're fighting against.

03:49.040 --> 03:49.520
Exactly.

03:49.520 --> 03:55.800
We have to talk about the current paradigm of classical computing and classical logic.

03:55.800 --> 04:06.660
Almost all traditional computation is built on a very specific, unquestioned assumption, which is that processes are functions.

04:07.020 --> 04:09.260
Like input goes in, output comes out.

04:09.520 --> 04:09.860
Right.

04:10.060 --> 04:11.700
They are input-output machines.

04:12.220 --> 04:21.480
You feed an input into a black box, the machine grinds away, performing various internal calculations, and it spits out a final result.

04:21.480 --> 04:28.020
And the crucial part of that assumption is what happens to all the grinding that went on inside the box.

04:28.180 --> 04:29.760
I mean, it gets tossed in the trash.

04:29.860 --> 04:31.640
It's considered auxiliary data.

04:32.080 --> 04:34.740
You bake the cake, so you don't need to keep the eggshells.

04:34.940 --> 04:36.620
That is the dominant philosophy.

04:36.620 --> 04:52.800
In classical semantics, which is the mathematical logic that dictates how we understand computer programs, the identity of a computation is defined entirely by the final observable output, or the fixed relationship between the input and the output.

04:53.160 --> 04:55.080
But SpherePop rejects that premise.

04:55.400 --> 04:55.580
Right.

04:55.640 --> 04:57.300
Like, at a molecular level.

04:57.560 --> 04:58.400
Oh, completely.

04:59.460 --> 05:02.480
SpherePop declares that computation is not a function.

05:03.240 --> 05:04.900
Computation is a history.

05:04.900 --> 05:15.360
The true identity of a process is the strictly ordered sequence of exclusions, the specific paths you permanently closed off, to arrive at the outcome.

05:15.900 --> 05:18.040
The journey isn't just a means to an end.

05:18.160 --> 05:21.180
The journey is the only thing that actually exists.

05:21.460 --> 05:27.640
To really wrap our heads around this SpherePop universe, we have to spend a little time in the old universe.

05:28.340 --> 05:33.000
We need to look at the mathematical status quo that Fliction is rebelling against.

05:33.060 --> 05:33.440
Right.

05:33.440 --> 05:39.500
And the primary villain in Fliction's narrative is a mathematical concept known as the trace operator.

05:40.260 --> 05:48.640
We need to understand what this operator is, and more importantly, what it intentionally, actively tries to erase from reality.

05:48.640 --> 05:52.060
Let's delve into the mathematics of that status quo.

05:52.820 --> 06:03.500
When computer scientists and mathematicians want to formally model complex systems, specifically systems that involve feedback loops, recursion, or things talking to themselves.

06:03.700 --> 06:05.260
Systems that loop back on themselves.

06:05.320 --> 06:05.660
Right.

06:05.820 --> 06:10.620
They typically rely on a structure called trace symmetric monoidal categories.

06:10.860 --> 06:12.940
Which sounds incredibly intimidating.

06:12.940 --> 06:22.020
Well, it does sound intimidating, but it was pioneered in the mid-1990s by mathematicians like Andre Joyal, Ross Street, and Dominic Verity.

06:22.320 --> 06:25.120
It was a brilliant breakthrough for its time.

06:25.580 --> 06:31.400
But the beating heart of this framework, the actual mechanism that makes it work, is the trace operator.

06:31.400 --> 06:31.960
Okay.

06:32.100 --> 06:43.660
In mathematical notation, you will often see it written as a capital TR with subscripts A and B, a superscript U, operating on a function F.

06:44.000 --> 06:44.260
Okay.

06:44.300 --> 06:51.720
I promised the listener we wouldn't overwhelm them with raw equations, so let's translate those letters into something tangible in the physical world.

06:51.720 --> 06:55.200
Like, what are A, B, and U actually doing?

06:55.320 --> 06:55.760
Fair enough.

06:56.500 --> 06:59.080
Imagine a complex machine on a factory floor.

06:59.720 --> 07:02.160
This machine represents our function, F.

07:02.680 --> 07:06.000
It has a main conveyor belt where raw materials come in.

07:06.200 --> 07:07.900
That's our external input, A.

07:08.160 --> 07:08.600
Got it.

07:08.740 --> 07:09.260
Input A.

07:09.300 --> 07:12.440
It also has a main conveyor belt where finished products roll out.

07:12.540 --> 07:14.420
That's our external output, B.

07:14.860 --> 07:16.500
But this machine is complicated.

07:16.500 --> 07:22.340
Sometimes a part needs more work, so the machine has an internal circular conveyor belt.

07:22.420 --> 07:22.800
Uh-huh.

07:23.040 --> 07:23.380
A loop.

07:23.720 --> 07:24.240
Exactly.

07:24.460 --> 07:31.580
It takes a half-finished part, let's call that intermediate data U, and loops it right back into its own gears to be processed again.

07:32.280 --> 07:38.720
The trace operator is a mathematical tool that looks at this entire factory setup and forcefully simplifies it.

07:38.800 --> 07:43.900
It essentially throws a giant tarp over the internal circular conveyor belt.

07:44.280 --> 07:45.760
That is exactly the visual.

07:45.760 --> 08:01.520
The trace operator mathematically asserts that the precise step-by-step internal workings on that feedback loop, U, are utterly irrelevant, provided we know the final stabilized effect on the external interface, the path from A to B.

08:01.760 --> 08:02.220
Wow.

08:02.400 --> 08:10.480
It takes a dynamic, messy, temporal loop and flattens it into a static, fixed-point input-output relation.

08:10.740 --> 08:13.260
So it's performing a deliberate act of amnesia.

08:13.260 --> 08:19.760
The math is explicitly saying, I refuse to care how many times the internal conveyor belt went around.

08:20.280 --> 08:27.600
I don't care if the machine struggled, if it almost broke down, or what intermediate shapes the metal took while it was inside the box.

08:28.000 --> 08:29.900
Just show me the final widget.

08:30.220 --> 08:30.520
Yes.

08:30.820 --> 08:33.200
The term for this in mathematics is quotienting.

08:33.540 --> 08:38.420
You are taking things that are technically different and forcing them into an equivalence class.

08:38.420 --> 08:40.640
You are declaring them the same.

08:40.880 --> 08:43.960
This reminds me of how we consume media sometimes.

08:44.820 --> 08:50.800
Reading the output of a trace operator is like reading a one-sentence plot summary of a two-hour movie.

08:51.000 --> 08:52.380
Oh, that's a good way to put it.

08:52.560 --> 08:52.820
Right.

08:52.820 --> 09:04.200
You go onto Wikipedia, you read the synopsis, and it just says, a young farm boy discovers a mystical power, destroys a massive space station, and saves the galaxy.

09:04.760 --> 09:08.540
It gives you the input farm boy and the output saved galaxy.

09:08.680 --> 09:10.140
But you miss the whole movie.

09:10.540 --> 09:11.100
Exactly.

09:11.520 --> 09:14.640
It completely annihilates the actual experience.

09:14.640 --> 09:22.140
It discards the sequence of scenes, the tension, the dialogue, the narrow escapes, the emotional choices the characters had to make.

09:22.520 --> 09:23.940
It gives you the flat PDF.

09:24.700 --> 09:30.720
SpherePop, on the other hand, wants the complete, unedited git commit log of the universe.

09:31.260 --> 09:41.380
Infliction uses a brilliant theoretical example to show why throwing a tarp over the internal mechanics is a catastrophic mistake if you care about true identity.

09:41.740 --> 09:42.660
Let's hear the example.

09:42.660 --> 09:52.620
Imagine you have two different computer programs, and both of them are designed to compute the simplest mathematical concept of possible, the identity function.

09:53.260 --> 09:57.460
They simply return whatever input you give them, completely unaltered.

09:57.780 --> 10:02.220
Like, you hand the program an apple, it hands you back the exact same apple.

10:02.360 --> 10:02.960
Precisely.

10:03.220 --> 10:04.500
Let's look at the first program.

10:04.800 --> 10:05.960
It is perfectly efficient.

10:06.420 --> 10:10.400
You hand it the input a, and in one millisecond, it hands back a.

10:11.140 --> 10:11.920
Simple enough.

10:11.920 --> 10:13.800
Now, let's look at the second program.

10:14.020 --> 10:14.900
You hand it A.

10:15.520 --> 10:17.280
But this program is chaotic.

10:17.840 --> 10:24.680
It takes that input and initiates 1,000 deeply nested complex recursive calls.

10:25.080 --> 10:32.160
It spins up massive internal loops, allocates memory, calculates wild tangential equations.

10:32.400 --> 10:33.920
It's doing a ton of unnecessary work.

10:33.920 --> 10:34.440
So much work.

10:34.540 --> 10:35.400
So much work.

10:35.400 --> 10:43.520
But then, by sheer mathematical design, all of those internal operations eventually perfectly cancel each other out.

10:44.040 --> 10:47.460
Ten minutes later, the machine whirs to a halt and hands you back A.

10:47.580 --> 10:57.400
Okay, so under the old paradigm, under Joyle, Street, and Verity's traced monoidal categories, how does the math view these two programs?

10:57.400 --> 11:03.520
Under trace semantics, those two programs denote the exact same mathematical morphism.

11:03.900 --> 11:06.780
They are considered fundamentally identical objects.

11:07.220 --> 11:08.060
Wait, identical?

11:08.200 --> 11:09.300
Completely identical.

11:09.840 --> 11:14.680
The trace operator looks at the first program and sees input A, output A.

11:14.680 --> 11:22.880
It looks at the 10-minute, 1,000-loop, chaotic program, throws a tarp over the loops, and sees input A, output A.

11:23.600 --> 11:27.120
The math declares there is zero difference between them.

11:27.820 --> 11:31.300
Infliction's framework looks at that and screams, are you kidding me?

11:31.500 --> 11:33.140
They're completely different.

11:33.300 --> 11:37.240
This is the core of what the text calls the sphere-pop refusal.

11:37.880 --> 11:43.180
It is an absolute uncompromising rejection of quotienting away history.

11:43.180 --> 11:49.080
In sphere-pop, those two programs are profoundly distinct entities.

11:49.420 --> 11:50.740
Because they took different paths.

11:50.820 --> 12:03.740
Because their causal chains differ, the actual chronological sequence of commitments, the physical time and thermodynamic energy spent, the events that took place in the convocational world, they are entirely different.

12:03.920 --> 12:09.320
So if fliction refuses to use traced categories, what is the mathematical alternative?

12:09.320 --> 12:13.460
I mean, if we aren't collapsing loops, what geometry are we building?

12:13.820 --> 12:20.900
The alternative introduced in the papers is called the free history category, denoted as H of omega.

12:21.600 --> 12:24.020
The word free is vital here.

12:24.600 --> 12:32.320
In abstract algebra, when you call an object free, it means it is generated with absolutely no imposed equivalences.

12:32.320 --> 12:37.280
So it's completely free of rules saying, this path equals that path.

12:37.360 --> 12:37.920
Exactly.

12:38.240 --> 12:40.480
Think of a free monoid in linguistics.

12:40.680 --> 12:43.400
It's just the set of all possible sequences of letters.

12:43.960 --> 12:49.220
There is no hidden rule that says the sequence ABC is equivalent to the sequence CBA.

12:49.700 --> 12:51.420
They were just distinct sequences.

12:51.740 --> 12:51.860
Right.

12:52.220 --> 12:55.360
The free history category treats actions the same way.

12:55.680 --> 12:58.940
It introduces zero relations between different histories.

12:58.940 --> 13:07.340
Every distinct granular sequence of computational commitments corresponds to a uniquely distinct mathematical morphism.

13:08.000 --> 13:12.540
What's fascinating here is the stark geometric contrast this creates.

13:12.780 --> 13:13.040
Oh, so.

13:13.360 --> 13:20.380
Well, in the old traced categories, the defining structural feature is a loop that gets forcibly collapsed into a point.

13:21.080 --> 13:24.900
In sphere pop, loops do not exist at the foundational level.

13:24.900 --> 13:28.640
The defining structural feature is a directed path.

13:29.260 --> 13:40.220
It is a one-way street forging through a space of possibilities, a sequence of words in a free monoid, and it never, ever loops back or forgets a single footstep.

13:40.220 --> 13:45.120
So, we've established that we are no longer allowed to just look at the final PDF.

13:45.300 --> 13:46.900
We have to look at the history of how it was written.

13:47.380 --> 13:55.120
But if I am a developer or just someone trying to understand this logically, what am I actually looking at?

13:55.160 --> 14:04.240
If I could hit the pause button on the universe or pause the sphere pop computation right in the middle of running, what is the actual anatomy of a moment?

14:04.240 --> 14:09.340
What does a state look like if it isn't just a list of current variable values?

14:10.180 --> 14:14.320
To answer that, we have to pull apart the fundamental data structure proposed in the papers.

14:14.880 --> 14:20.600
In a traditional Python or C++ program, the state is literally just a snapshot of memory.

14:21.160 --> 14:22.840
Variable x equals 5.

14:23.220 --> 14:24.840
Variable y equals hello.

14:25.080 --> 14:26.180
Right, the current status.

14:26.680 --> 14:30.760
But in sphere pop, a state is not a single snapshot.

14:31.340 --> 14:32.220
It is a pair.

14:32.220 --> 14:42.840
It consists of two entirely different, structurally opposed mathematical objects, which the notation refers to as omega sub t and h sub t.

14:43.040 --> 14:46.380
Omega sub t and h sub t.

14:46.500 --> 14:49.420
And the t obviously stands for a specific moment in time.

14:49.780 --> 14:52.060
Let's break those two symbols down for the listener.

14:52.360 --> 14:54.160
Let's start with omega sub t.

14:54.600 --> 14:56.940
This is the residual option space.

14:56.940 --> 15:01.480
It represents the universe of everything that still remains possible at time t.

15:01.480 --> 15:10.200
You can visualize it as an undifferentiated floating cloud of futures that have not yet been permanently excluded or chosen.

15:10.700 --> 15:12.240
Okay, the cloud of the possible.

15:12.580 --> 15:15.900
Then you have the second half of the pair, h sub t.

15:16.360 --> 15:17.720
This is the commitment history.

15:18.360 --> 15:27.380
It is the strict chronological ledger of everything that has been explicitly selected, committed to, and etched into reality up to time t.

15:27.380 --> 15:33.420
Now, I have to admit, when I was first reading through the source material, this is where my brain started to rebel a little bit.

15:33.640 --> 15:35.220
I want to push back on this structure.

15:35.300 --> 15:35.660
Go for it.

15:35.660 --> 15:43.420
If the history, h sub t, is this meticulous, unbroken ledger of every single choice we've ever made,

15:44.240 --> 15:51.440
why on earth do we need to drag around this second mathematical object, the option space, omega sub t?

15:51.440 --> 15:53.340
It feels highly redundant.

15:53.900 --> 15:57.940
I mean, if I have a perfect receipt of exactly what I bought at the grocery store,

15:58.660 --> 16:05.440
why do I care about maintaining a mathematical set that tracks all the items still sitting on the shelves that I didn't buy?

16:05.700 --> 16:15.080
Your intuition to question that is incredibly common because we are so conditioned to only value the positive, the things that are.

16:15.080 --> 16:19.880
But in sphere pop, the unchosen is just as structurally important as the chosen.

16:20.600 --> 16:25.380
Understanding why is the key to grasping Flixian's entire philosophy of agency.

16:25.800 --> 16:26.420
Let me see it.

16:26.540 --> 16:28.060
Why is the empty shelf important?

16:28.200 --> 16:31.780
Because the history, h sub t, only tells you what did happen.

16:32.100 --> 16:35.940
The option space, omega sub t, records what could have happened but didn't.

16:36.260 --> 16:39.880
You need both to mathematically prove that a choice actually occurred.

16:39.880 --> 16:48.720
Tracking both halves of the pair is the only way the system can distinguish between a genuine exercise of agency and a mere lack of alternatives.

16:48.940 --> 16:53.840
Okay, the restaurant analogy from the joyous sphere pop makes this click perfectly.

16:54.160 --> 16:55.580
Let's adapt that for our listeners.

16:57.080 --> 16:59.720
Imagine you and I are trying to figure out where to go for dinner.

17:00.560 --> 17:06.780
Tomorrow, someone asks us where we went, and we hand them our historical ledger, our h sub t.

17:06.780 --> 17:11.200
The ledger has exactly one entry, Italian.

17:11.440 --> 17:16.980
And if they only possess that ledger, they have a critically incomplete picture of reality.

17:17.140 --> 17:20.620
Because they have no idea how we ended up at the Italian place.

17:20.760 --> 17:22.020
I mean, think about scenario A.

17:22.260 --> 17:25.520
You and I sat in the car for 20 minutes having a fierce debate.

17:25.920 --> 17:30.240
We looked at menus for a Mexican restaurant, a sushi place, and the Italian spot.

17:30.520 --> 17:31.780
We weighed the options.

17:31.780 --> 17:36.400
We realized we really wanted pasta, and we deliberately selected Italian.

17:36.820 --> 17:37.900
That is a choice.

17:38.160 --> 17:38.280
Right.

17:38.640 --> 17:40.520
Now, contrast that with scenario B.

17:40.920 --> 17:41.600
Scenario B.

17:42.020 --> 17:44.060
It's 11.30 p.m. on a Tuesday.

17:44.640 --> 17:46.140
We're driving through a small town.

17:46.240 --> 17:47.540
The Mexican place is closed.

17:47.900 --> 17:50.180
The sushi place burned down three years ago.

17:50.700 --> 17:55.540
The Italian restaurant is literally the only building with its lights on within 50 miles.

17:55.760 --> 17:56.440
We eat there.

17:56.660 --> 17:58.040
A totally different reality.

17:58.520 --> 17:58.980
Exactly.

17:58.980 --> 18:04.500
If you look at the H-sub-T ledger for scenario B, it still just says Italian.

18:05.280 --> 18:07.720
But in scenario B, Italian wasn't a choice.

18:07.860 --> 18:09.300
It was a hostage situation.

18:09.800 --> 18:13.020
It was an inevitability dictated by the environment.

18:13.200 --> 18:14.940
That distinction is everything.

18:15.360 --> 18:20.420
By strictly tracking omega-sub-T, the system captures the context of genuine choice.

18:21.060 --> 18:28.380
In scenario A, the omega-sub-T at 7.00 p.m. contained Mexican, sushi, and Italian.

18:29.080 --> 18:33.780
By choosing Italian, you actively slaughtered the Mexican and sushi futures.

18:34.040 --> 18:34.180
Whoa.

18:34.680 --> 18:39.740
In scenario B, the omega-sub-T at 11.30 p.m. only contained Italian.

18:39.940 --> 18:43.020
No futures were excluded because no alternatives existed.

18:43.540 --> 18:48.500
The presence of the unchosen is what gives semantic weight and meaning to the chosen.

18:48.500 --> 18:56.080
And Flicksheen goes out of their way to highlight a very specific mathematical asymmetry between these two halves of the state pair, right?

18:56.120 --> 18:57.480
Like, they aren't built the same way.

18:57.540 --> 18:59.800
The asymmetry is profound and intentional.

19:00.360 --> 19:04.060
Omega-sub-T, the option space, is defined as an unordered set.

19:04.380 --> 19:07.300
It has no sequence, no chronological priority.

19:07.660 --> 19:10.640
It is just a hazy cloud of coexisting potentials.

19:11.040 --> 19:13.460
H-sub-T, however, is a strictly ordered list.

19:13.460 --> 19:16.320
It is a rigid, unbending sequence of events.

19:16.320 --> 19:21.100
The future is an unordered cloud, and the past is a rigid chain.

19:21.700 --> 19:25.880
That is a direct mathematical translation of the arrow of time.

19:26.240 --> 19:32.920
It's like they're baking the laws of thermodynamics and entropy right into the basic data structure of the code.

19:32.920 --> 19:35.900
It perfectly mirrors macroscopic physics.

19:36.180 --> 19:36.300
Yeah.

19:36.460 --> 19:39.600
The future is an undifferentiated space of potential.

19:39.940 --> 19:47.880
But the moment a possibility is actualized, the moment you grab it from the cloud, it becomes part of a strict, immutable sequence.

19:48.380 --> 19:53.160
And because it's an ordered list, you cannot commute the past.

19:53.520 --> 19:53.740
Commute.

19:54.580 --> 20:02.720
Commutativity is a property in math where the order of operations doesn't matter, like how 2 plus 3 is the same as 3 plus 2.

20:03.520 --> 20:07.720
Sphere Pop says history is explicitly non-commutative.

20:08.060 --> 20:10.360
Give me an example of non-commutative history.

20:11.240 --> 20:12.280
Like, in real life.

20:12.420 --> 20:12.740
Sure.

20:13.600 --> 20:24.480
Choosing to get married and then choosing to drop out of college is structurally, historically, and causally a completely different universe than choosing to drop out of college and then choosing to get married.

20:24.560 --> 20:25.040
Ah, I see.

20:25.500 --> 20:30.300
The items in the list might be exactly the same, but the sequence dictates the reality.

20:30.300 --> 20:33.860
